Invariant sums of perfect powers

We are interested in finding nontrivial sums of perfect powers that are exponentiation invariant. This means that if we swap the bases with the exponents, the sum remains the same.

Strongly Power Invariant Numbers (SPINs): Natural numbers n∈Nn∈N equal to an exponentiation invariant sum of unique non-invariant perfect powers ab,a>1,b>1ab,a>1,b>1. That is, for some k>1k>1 we can write:
n=∑i=1kabii=∑i=1kbaii,ai>1,bi>1,abii≠baii,(i≠j⟹{ai,bi}≠{aj,bj}).n=∑i=1kaibi=∑i=1kbiai,ai>1,bi>1,aibi≠biai,(i≠j⟹{ai,bi}≠{aj,bj}).
Then, nn is a kk-order SPIN and we write n∈Gkn∈Gk.

Classification: To classify these numbers more nicely, we split GkGk into either union of 2k−12k−1 disjoint subsets
Gk=G(0)k∪G(1)k∪⋯∪G(2k−1−1)k=G(2k−1)k∪G(2k−2)k∪⋯∪G(2k−1)k,Gk=Gk(0)∪Gk(1)∪⋯∪Gk(2k−1−1)=Gk(2k−1)∪Gk(2k−2)∪⋯∪Gk(2k−1),
where bb in G(b)kGk(b) represents the binary evaluation of vector vn=(sgn(ai−bi),i=1,,k)vn=(sgn⁡(ai−bi),i=1,,k), for sgn(x)={01x<0x>0sgn⁡(x)={0x<01x>0, under the assumption that (i<j⟹max{abii−baii,baii−abii}<max{abjj−bajj,bajj−abjj})(i<j⟹max{aibi−biai,biai−aibi}<max{ajbj−bjaj,bjaj−ajbj}).
We write n∈G(b)kn∈Gk(b) and say that nn is a kk-order bb-genus SPIN.

Order k<5k<5 examples

Conjecture: If k<5k<5, then Gk=∅Gk=∅. That is, there are no SPINs of order less than 55.

If a (counter) example exists, it is larger than n>1020n>1020. Only three "almost" (counter) examples are known:
1546311916113===27+82+54+36−1229+63+73+211−1234+82+65+213+12===72+28+45+63+1292+36+37+112+1243+28+56+132−121546=27+82+54+36−12=72+28+45+63+123119=29+63+73+211−12=92+36+37+112+1216113=34+82+65+213+12=43+28+56+132−12
If it weren't for the total error of 11, they would belong to G(6)4G4(6), because their vn=(0,1,1,0)vn=(0,1,1,0) if you look at the LHS. Alternatively, if you look at the RHS you can also say that they would belong to G(9)4G4(9), because there vn=(1,0,0,1)vn=(1,0,0,1).

WLOG, from now on we can observe only the classification relative to the LHS, as it is symmetric to the RHS one.

Order k=5k=5 examples

Up to n≤1020n≤1020, only 1414 examples or 55-order SPINS are known. It is conjectured that these are the only examples.

Up to this limit, other bb-genus sets G(b)kGk(b) are empty.

Up to this limit, the largest known "near" example (the LHS and RHS differ by 11) is:
8590001473=28+216+416+232+332−12=82+162+164+322+233+128590001473=28+216+416+232+332−12=82+162+164+322+233+12
If it weren't for the error of 11, it would be a G(1)5G5(1) example.

Notice that "near" examples of kk-order correspond to examples of (k+1)(k+1)-order that contain {ai,bi}={2,3}{ai,bi}={2,3}. This is because 23−32=−123−32=−1 and 32−23=132−23=1, so we can cancel out the error by adding this term to the sum.

Instead of keeping track of kk-order "near" examples, we can instead look at (k+1)(k+1)-order examples with term {2,3}{2,3}.

I would conjecture that there are infinitely many examples of 66-order SPINs.

I would also conjecture that the same holds for any fixed k≥6k≥6.

Order k>6k>6 examples

The larger the kk, the more examples we can find.

I did not feel the need to list these examples as they get quite numerous.
